// Update Log Manager
// Logs document/diagram/design changes with diffs and timestamps, enabling content reconstruction at any past point.

The update log is stored at {sessionPath}/update-log.json.
Each resource type (documents, diagrams, designs, spreadsheets, snippets) has its own map.
Each resource entry holds the original content and an ordered list of change diffs.
Writes are atomic: content is written to a .tmp file and renamed into place.

FUNCTION constructor(basePath)
  Derive logFilePath as basePath/update-log.json.

---

FUNCTION logUpdate(resourceType, resourceId, oldContent, newContent, diff) -> void
  CALLS: loadLog (update-log-manager), saveLog (update-log-manager)
  Skip if old and new content are identical.
  Load the log. IF this is the first update for the resource, record the original content.
  Use the provided diff or fall back to { oldString: oldContent, newString: newContent }.
  Append a ChangeEntry with the current ISO timestamp and diff. Save the log.

---

FUNCTION getHistory(resourceType, resourceId) -> DocumentLogEntry | null
  CALLS: loadLog (update-log-manager)
  Load the log and return the entry for the resource, or null if none exists.

---

FUNCTION replayToTimestamp(resourceType, resourceId, timestamp) -> string
  CALLS: getHistory (update-log-manager)
  Load history. Throw if no history exists for the resource.
  Start with the original content. Apply each change whose timestamp is at or before the target,
  replacing oldString with newString in order. Stop at the first change past the target.
  Return the reconstructed content.

---

FUNCTION loadLog() -> UpdateLog
  Private. IF log file does not exist, return an empty log with all resource type keys.
  Read and parse the JSON. Backfill any missing resource type keys for backwards compatibility.
  On any error, warn and return an empty log.

---

FUNCTION saveLog(log) -> void
  Private. Serialize the log to a .tmp file, then atomically rename it to the final path.
  Clean up the .tmp file on rename failure. Throw on any unrecoverable error.
